<TITLE> AL accepts city, municipal polls </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 27 (bdnews24.com)  The Awami League has accepted the holding of elections to four city corporations and nine municipalities on Aug 4, according to the schedule announced by the Election Commission. After a two-day meeting of the party's working committee that ended Friday evening, AL acting president Zillur Rahman told reporters: "We have decided unanimously to accept the election schedule." "Awami League will go to elections for the cause of peace and democracy." The party had previously demanded the holding of parliamentary elections ahead of any other polls. The AL acting president said: "The two-day working committee meeting discussed only one agendawhether to go to elections." The Election Commission announced the schedule on June 20 for simultaneous voting in four city corporation and nine municipality polls on Aug 4. According to the full schedule, the date for submission of nomination papers is July 3, scrutiny of nominations on July 6-7 and last date for withdrawal of candidature is July 13. Demanding the withdrawal of the state of emergency before the city and municipal elections on Aug 4, Zillur said: "Despite our repeated demands, the state of emergency has not been lifted." "This is disappointing. Awami League thinks the state of emergency should be lifted before the city and municipal elections." He urged all to bolster public opinion for the release of Sheikh Hasina, saying: "She will return. Public opinion will have to be built up so, that after her return she cannot be interned again." Awami League acting general secretary Syed Ashraful Islam told bdnews24.com: "We want to sit with the 14-party alliance and seek candidates for the local polls from the grassroots level." When asked whether Awami League would go to elections if the emergency were not lifted, he said: "Everything will be discussed in our political dialogue session. We hope the government will give importance to our statements." "If elections are to be held, the government will have to take the views of political parties into cognizance." The working committee meeting resumed 5pm Friday at the party's Dhanmondi offices, after being adjourned Thursday. bdnew
